00:06:04.320 --> 00:06:07.440
And don't auto play it again.

00:06:07.440 --> 00:06:08.386
Thanks.

00:06:08.386 --> 00:06:10.290
[CHUCKLE]

00:06:10.290 --> 00:06:14.180
They get the user quickly
to where they want to go.

00:06:14.180 --> 00:06:16.560
In a conversational
dialogue, we know

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:21.000
users drop off each time
another question is asked.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:25.090
So the fewer steps to
complete a task, the better.

00:06:25.090 --> 00:06:27.685
Keep your users engaged by
avoiding needless banter.

00:06:35.940 --> 00:06:39.480
Tip 2, add a persona.

00:06:39.480 --> 00:06:42.660
We want simple
conversations, but users also

00:06:42.660 --> 00:06:47.100
want to feel connected and
engaged with your action.

00:06:47.100 --> 00:06:50.340
Developing a persona
or a personality

00:06:50.340 --> 00:06:52.530
and incorporating
it into your action

00:06:52.530 --> 00:06:54.060
really brings it to life.

00:06:57.500 --> 00:07:00.500
Take, for example,
a pizza restaurant.

00:07:00.500 --> 00:07:03.030
There are many types
of pizza restaurants.

00:07:03.030 --> 00:07:07.100
There is that upscale brick
oven pizzeria, or that New York

00:07:07.100 --> 00:07:09.980
walk-up where you can
grab a quick slice,

00:07:09.980 --> 00:07:13.730
and the local
beach-side local spot.

00:07:13.730 --> 00:07:17.210
Each one is going to
communicate in a different way.

00:07:17.210 --> 00:07:20.540
And your action
can exemplify this.

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:22.880
By defining a
thorough persona, you

00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:25.940
can draw users into your action.

00:07:25.940 --> 00:07:27.830
We'll do some acting again.

00:07:27.830 --> 00:07:30.530
Sunil will play the pizza
action, and I'll be the user.

00:07:34.859 --> 00:07:38.688
SUNIL VEMURI: Hello, what
would you like today?

00:07:38.688 --> 00:07:40.761
TORI BURMEISTER: Pizza.

00:07:40.761 --> 00:07:44.490
SUNIL VEMURI: OK, what
toppings would you like to add?

00:07:44.490 --> 00:07:46.590
TORI BURMEISTER:
Pretty bland, right?

00:07:46.590 --> 00:07:48.400
It's fine.

00:07:48.400 --> 00:07:51.120
But I'm not sure we expressed
anything about our brand

00:07:51.120 --> 00:07:52.549
or who we are.

00:07:52.549 --> 00:07:53.340
Let's try it again.

00:07:56.286 --> 00:07:58.690
SUNIL VEMURI: Cowabunga, dude.

00:07:58.690 --> 00:08:00.811
What can I getcha?

00:08:00.811 --> 00:08:02.890
TORI BURMEISTER: Pizza!

00:08:02.890 --> 00:08:03.780
SUNIL VEMURI: Great!

00:08:03.780 --> 00:08:06.286
What flavor do you crave?

00:08:06.286 --> 00:08:08.860
TORI BURMEISTER: Maybe we've
taken this one a little far,

00:08:08.860 --> 00:08:10.870
but you get the idea.

00:08:10.870 --> 00:08:13.810
Our persona is a local surfer.

00:08:13.810 --> 00:08:15.940
Personality can't be avoided.

00:08:15.940 --> 00:08:19.480
It's human nature to attach
personality to things.

00:08:19.480 --> 00:08:21.700
And we're hardwired
to look for meaning

00:08:21.700 --> 00:08:23.830
in the things around us.

00:08:23.830 --> 00:08:26.710
People will attribute a
personality with your action

00:08:26.710 --> 00:08:29.830
regardless of whether you
think about it or not.

00:08:29.830 --> 00:08:34.309
It's better to control the
perception and define it.

00:08:34.309 --> 00:08:36.909
Well-defined personas
also increase

00:08:36.909 --> 00:08:39.190
the emotional connection.

00:08:39.190 --> 00:08:43.260
This leads to increased usage,
retention, and brand loyalty.

00:08:47.160 --> 00:08:49.950
Things to think about when
you're defining your persona

00:08:49.950 --> 00:08:52.740
is what state is the
user going to be in?

00:08:52.740 --> 00:08:54.580
Are they looking to relaxed?

00:08:54.580 --> 00:08:56.750
Are they excited?

00:08:56.750 --> 00:09:01.104
And based off of that, what
role should your agent play?

00:09:01.104 --> 00:09:02.520
Looking at these
attributes, these

00:09:02.520 --> 00:09:04.510
are a couple of
different options.

00:09:04.510 --> 00:09:06.310
The first might be
a teacher, someone

00:09:06.310 --> 00:09:10.720
who is patient and
helpful and encouraging.

00:09:10.720 --> 00:09:15.270
And then a friend might be
playful, casual, and silly.

00:09:15.270 --> 00:09:17.040
Whereas a helper,
you're going to want

00:09:17.040 --> 00:09:21.030
to be attentive and
proactive and succinct.

00:09:21.030 --> 00:09:25.390
We recommend you define the
persona at the design phase

00:09:25.390 --> 00:09:28.020
and then shape your
conversation around it.

00:09:28.020 --> 00:09:30.111
It can make a big difference.

00:09:33.408 --> 00:09:38.360
SUNIL VEMURI: Tip number 3,
users can be unpredictable.

00:09:38.360 --> 00:09:42.730
They can use products in ways
that we don't always expect.

00:09:42.730 --> 00:09:45.340
In the case of
conversational actions,

00:09:45.340 --> 00:09:48.138
they might say something
that you didn't anticipate.

00:09:51.070 --> 00:09:52.390
Let's try this dialogue.

00:09:52.390 --> 00:09:57.130
This time I'll be the user
and Tori will be the action.

00:09:57.130 --> 00:09:58.705
I'd like an ice cream cone.

00:09:58.705 --> 00:09:59.830
TORI BURMEISTER: Yummy.

00:09:59.830 --> 00:10:01.285
What size do you want?

00:10:01.285 --> 00:10:02.575
SUNIL VEMURI: A double.

00:10:02.575 --> 00:10:05.170
TORI BURMEISTER: Sorry,
what size do you want?

00:10:05.170 --> 00:10:09.040
Small, medium, or large?

00:10:09.040 --> 00:10:12.400
SUNIL VEMURI: OK, the
grammar was not robust.

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:17.050
The action didn't understand
a common variation of medium,

00:10:17.050 --> 00:10:19.177
in this case, I said double.

00:10:19.177 --> 00:10:21.760
Now, I don't know about you, but
I've been to ice cream shops.

00:10:21.760 --> 00:10:24.890
And you can ask for different
sizes in different ways.

00:10:24.890 --> 00:10:27.250
So you want your grammars
to be able to handle

00:10:27.250 --> 00:10:30.150
all of these different common
variations that might come up.

00:10:34.300 --> 00:10:36.960
Let me show you how
you can approach this.

00:10:36.960 --> 00:10:40.920
Using Dialogflow, there's
a simple way to do this.

00:10:40.920 --> 00:10:43.620
First, training
phrases-- this is

00:10:43.620 --> 00:10:46.380
where you can include some
of the common different ways

00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:48.570
somebody might say
the same phrase.

00:10:48.570 --> 00:10:52.110
So for example, can
I have a medium?

00:10:52.110 --> 00:10:54.110
I'll have two scoops.

00:10:54.110 --> 00:10:56.400
A double, please.

00:10:56.400 --> 00:10:58.590
You can include all of
these different phrases

00:10:58.590 --> 00:11:01.200
in the training phrase
section so that the system

00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:03.030
will understand
that users might ask

00:11:03.030 --> 00:11:05.560
for things in different ways.

00:11:05.560 --> 00:11:08.580
The second is synonyms.

00:11:08.580 --> 00:11:11.470
Let's take another
example, rain boots.

00:11:11.470 --> 00:11:14.640
So there are many different ways
somebody might say rain boots.

00:11:14.640 --> 00:11:18.840
It could be gumboots,
galoshes, wellies.

00:11:18.840 --> 00:11:21.330
You can include all of these
different kinds of synonyms

00:11:21.330 --> 00:11:24.630
and variations as part of
the interface and Dialogflow

00:11:24.630 --> 00:11:27.420
so that users will be able
to give their responses

00:11:27.420 --> 00:11:29.970
with these kind of variations.

00:11:29.970 --> 00:11:31.510
But there's another part.

00:11:31.510 --> 00:11:34.770
The more examples you
give, the better Dialogflow

00:11:34.770 --> 00:11:37.440
can learn from those
examples because it does

00:11:37.440 --> 00:11:39.150
have learning capabilities.

00:11:39.150 --> 00:11:43.210
And then it can learn new
ways that the user has

00:11:43.210 --> 00:11:44.970
expressed these same concepts.

00:11:44.970 --> 00:11:46.650
So more examples, the better.

00:11:49.399 --> 00:11:50.940
Let's take a look
at an action called

00:11:50.940 --> 00:11:53.400
Timeout that illustrates this.

00:11:53.400 --> 00:11:56.790
Timeout tells you about
events in the United Kingdom.

00:11:56.790 --> 00:11:58.950
On this first screen,
Timeout is asking

00:11:58.950 --> 00:12:01.500
for a day you like to go out.

00:12:01.500 --> 00:12:04.350
The user responds
with, I don't know.

00:12:04.350 --> 00:12:06.320
Instead of asking
the user again,

00:12:06.320 --> 00:12:09.300
Timeout recognizes the
phrase "I don't know"

00:12:09.300 --> 00:12:10.560
and gives a helpful response.

00:12:13.150 --> 00:12:15.350
In the second
screen, Timeout again

00:12:15.350 --> 00:12:18.110
asks if I want to go out
today, tomorrow, or Saturday.

00:12:20.720 --> 00:12:22.970
Excuse me, today,
tomorrow, or Sunday.

00:12:22.970 --> 00:12:25.640
The user responded
with Saturday.

00:12:25.640 --> 00:12:27.380
And again, Timeout handled it--

00:12:27.380 --> 00:12:30.170
common variations
and things outside

00:12:30.170 --> 00:12:34.320
of what the prompt asked for.

00:12:34.320 --> 00:12:38.100
And on the right, the user was
being a little clever here,

00:12:38.100 --> 00:12:41.290
and they asked for
something funny.

00:12:41.290 --> 00:12:46.070
Timeout responded with humor,
so kind of like an Easter egg.

00:12:46.070 --> 00:12:49.910
So these are some of the ways to
make your actions more robust.

00:12:49.910 --> 00:12:55.060
But there's more to
conversational excellence.

00:12:55.060 --> 00:12:58.670
Users can still say
unexpected things.

00:12:58.670 --> 00:13:00.580
And when people
talk to each other,

00:13:00.580 --> 00:13:03.610
if the listener doesn't
understand the speaker,

00:13:03.610 --> 00:13:07.010
they work cooperatively
to figure it out.

00:13:07.010 --> 00:13:09.610
They ask for corrections
or rewordings

00:13:09.610 --> 00:13:11.320
or try to give
some hints to help

00:13:11.320 --> 00:13:13.919
move the conversation forward.

00:13:13.919 --> 00:13:15.460
Let's take a look
at an example here.

00:13:21.570 --> 00:13:25.065
TORI BURMEISTER:
When is the event?

00:13:25.065 --> 00:13:27.990
SUNIL VEMURI: Tomorrow.

00:13:27.990 --> 00:13:29.900
TORI BURMEISTER: I
don't understand.

00:13:29.900 --> 00:13:32.454
When is the event?

00:13:32.454 --> 00:13:34.970
SUNIL VEMURI: Uh, Wednesday.

00:13:34.970 --> 00:13:36.790
TORI BURMEISTER: I
don't understand.

00:13:36.790 --> 00:13:38.460
When is the event?

00:13:38.460 --> 00:13:41.965
SUNIL VEMURI: Wednesday!

00:13:41.965 --> 00:13:43.850
TORI BURMEISTER: I
don't understand.

00:13:43.850 --> 00:13:44.840
When is the event?

00:13:44.840 --> 00:13:46.050
SUNIL VEMURI: Argh!

00:13:46.050 --> 00:13:46.850
Frustrating!

00:13:46.850 --> 00:13:49.730
But I'm sure you've
heard something

00:13:49.730 --> 00:13:51.740
like this before when
you've talk to a computer.

00:13:51.740 --> 00:13:54.530
This is hopefully not
something unfamiliar.

00:13:54.530 --> 00:13:57.230
The action is repetitive
and unhelpful.

00:13:57.230 --> 00:13:59.130
It gives the same response.

00:13:59.130 --> 00:14:01.730
It's not noticing that
the user is earnestly

00:14:01.730 --> 00:14:05.010
trying to move the
conversation forward.

00:14:05.010 --> 00:14:08.680
So here's what we recommend.

00:14:08.680 --> 00:14:11.920
For the initial prompt,
you can give that.

00:14:11.920 --> 00:14:16.600
Now, there's two types of errors
that we recommend you handle.

00:14:16.600 --> 00:14:19.060
The first is called no match.

00:14:19.060 --> 00:14:20.710
This is when the
user says something,

00:14:20.710 --> 00:14:22.690
and the action didn't handle it.

00:14:22.690 --> 00:14:25.970
When this happens you want to
get the user back on track.

00:14:25.970 --> 00:14:28.740
We recommend the first
reprompt to be what

00:14:28.740 --> 00:14:30.632
is called a rapid reprompt.

00:14:30.632 --> 00:14:32.590
You give essentially the
same response or maybe

00:14:32.590 --> 00:14:36.380
a slight variation but don't
go too much further than that.

00:14:36.380 --> 00:14:39.040
And if the user still
doesn't give something

00:14:39.040 --> 00:14:41.290
that you can't
handle, here's where

00:14:41.290 --> 00:14:43.270
we call escalating detail.

00:14:43.270 --> 00:14:44.770
Make it a little
bit more elaborate,

00:14:44.770 --> 00:14:47.140
perhaps even an
example of what's

00:14:47.140 --> 00:14:50.540
something they can say to help
move the conversation forward.

00:14:50.540 --> 00:14:53.830
And after that,
stop reprompting.

00:14:53.830 --> 00:14:55.870
Don't pester the user.

00:14:55.870 --> 00:14:59.210
We find the sequence
works very well.

00:14:59.210 --> 00:15:01.800
Now, there's another type of
error that's called no input.

00:15:04.710 --> 00:15:07.260
This means the user
didn't say anything,

00:15:07.260 --> 00:15:10.260
or maybe the system didn't
hear what the user said.

00:15:10.260 --> 00:15:13.050
Perhaps they were thinking
about what they wanted to say,

00:15:13.050 --> 00:15:14.980
or they got confused
by the prompt,

00:15:14.980 --> 00:15:17.220
weren't sure how to respond.

00:15:17.220 --> 00:15:21.180
Like no match, we recommend
this three stage reprompting

00:15:21.180 --> 00:15:23.150
to help the user along.

00:15:23.150 --> 00:15:25.140
And with these six
reprompts, you're

00:15:25.140 --> 00:15:27.960
well on your way to build a
helpful conversation experience

00:15:27.960 --> 00:15:30.360
that keeps the user on track.

00:15:30.360 --> 00:15:31.520
Let's see how to code this.

00:15:36.350 --> 00:15:41.140
In Dialogflow you create what's
called a fallback intent.

00:15:41.140 --> 00:15:44.020
Then, in your web code,
you simply create an array

00:15:44.020 --> 00:15:48.310
with the three reprompts,
add a counter and some logic,

00:15:48.310 --> 00:15:49.707
so you return the right prompt.

00:15:49.707 --> 00:15:50.290
And that's it.

00:15:54.020 --> 00:15:57.200
Great design delights users
and keeps them coming back.

00:15:57.200 --> 00:16:01.760
Remember, keep your dialogue
short, include a persona,

00:16:01.760 --> 00:16:06.080
make robust grammars that handle
common variations and synonyms,

00:16:06.080 --> 00:16:08.550
handle errors like no
match and no input.

00:16:12.190 --> 00:16:14.900
TORI BURMEISTER: So now
you have the design basics.

00:16:14.900 --> 00:16:17.370
Let's make it more
fun and personalized.

00:16:21.300 --> 00:16:25.230
Tip 5, evolve with your user.

00:16:25.230 --> 00:16:27.450
When you have a follow up
conversation with someone

00:16:27.450 --> 00:16:30.850
you know, do you
introduce yourself again?

00:16:30.850 --> 00:16:34.200
If you know their address,
do you ask it again?

00:16:34.200 --> 00:16:36.570
Same goes for actions.

00:16:36.570 --> 00:16:40.650
Be there with help and
options when the user needs it

00:16:40.650 --> 00:16:44.640
but default to the simplest and
most personalized conversation

00:16:44.640 --> 00:16:45.540
for your user.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:52.720
So here's a horoscope
action, Tauro Horoscopo.

00:16:52.720 --> 00:16:54.030
It's in Portuguese.

00:16:54.030 --> 00:16:56.040
And if you don't
speak Portuguese,

00:16:56.040 --> 00:16:58.920
and you don't happen to
have Google Translate handy,

00:16:58.920 --> 00:17:01.170
let me tell you
what's happening.

00:17:01.170 --> 00:17:03.900
The first time the user
launches the action,

00:17:03.900 --> 00:17:06.089
it asks for the horoscope sign.

00:17:06.089 --> 00:17:09.630
On subsequent launches, it
doesn't and simply reuses

00:17:09.630 --> 00:17:11.310
the previous answer.

00:17:11.310 --> 00:17:12.839
This is great.

00:17:12.839 --> 00:17:14.430
Something as simple
as that could

00:17:14.430 --> 00:17:17.859
create a much better
experience for your user.

00:17:17.859 --> 00:17:20.069
Another iteration
on this could be

00:17:20.069 --> 00:17:22.530
when the user
invokes the action,

00:17:22.530 --> 00:17:25.560
you just give them their
horoscope right away.

00:17:25.560 --> 00:17:29.820
There are plenty examples
of good personalization.

00:17:29.820 --> 00:17:34.050
If you're a food action, you can
remember that I'm a vegetarian

00:17:34.050 --> 00:17:36.240
and focus on those choices.

00:17:36.240 --> 00:17:39.660
If you're a fitness action,
you can remember workouts,

00:17:39.660 --> 00:17:42.690
sounds, durations
that the user likes

00:17:42.690 --> 00:17:43.940
and use those as the defaults.

00:17:49.010 --> 00:17:51.290
Now we'll take a
look at the code.

00:17:51.290 --> 00:17:55.370
With a user info API, you
can get the user's name,

00:17:55.370 --> 00:17:58.190
anonymize user ID, and more.

00:17:58.190 --> 00:18:00.110
You could use this
to know if it's

00:18:00.110 --> 00:18:03.860
the same user on
subsequent invocations.

00:18:03.860 --> 00:18:07.100
There are also more robust
solutions using OAuth

00:18:07.100 --> 00:18:09.650
for logged in experiences.

00:18:09.650 --> 00:18:12.440
So here in the code you
can see we're checking

00:18:12.440 --> 00:18:14.330
if we've seen the user before.

00:18:14.330 --> 00:18:16.970
If we haven't, we
do the introduction.

00:18:16.970 --> 00:18:20.510
If we have, we attempt to
retrieve the horoscope sign

00:18:20.510 --> 00:18:24.080
and then continue on
with the conversation.

00:18:24.080 --> 00:18:27.440
What we want you to
remember from evolving

00:18:27.440 --> 00:18:31.700
with the users is, one,
get rid of the intro

00:18:31.700 --> 00:18:34.670
if the user is familiar
with it, and two,

00:18:34.670 --> 00:18:37.405
become more personalized
as you learn about them.

00:18:37.405 --> 00:18:39.530
Don't keep asking for things
that you already know.

00:18:43.715 --> 00:18:45.980
SUNIL VEMURI: We've all
heard computer generated text

00:18:45.980 --> 00:18:47.395
to speech.

00:18:47.395 --> 00:18:49.520
It's the technology that
takes text and converts it

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:50.330
into speech.

00:18:50.330 --> 00:18:53.530
And Google offers some
really nice text to speech.

00:18:53.530 --> 00:18:55.190
But do you know
what's even better?

00:18:55.190 --> 00:18:56.480
Media.

00:18:56.480 --> 00:18:57.980
Here's two tips for
the price of one

00:18:57.980 --> 00:19:01.730
to make your actions
sound awesome.

00:19:01.730 --> 00:19:04.430
First, the media response API--

00:19:04.430 --> 00:19:08.280
this let's you include
media clips in your action.

00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:11.600
Suppose I'm building an action
that plays famous speeches.

00:19:11.600 --> 00:19:15.800
I can call this API to include
the actual audio, some images,

00:19:15.800 --> 00:19:17.480
and with some controls.

00:19:17.480 --> 00:19:20.414
Let's give it a listen.

