00:22:33.320 --> 00:22:35.620
Tip number 7, adjust
to your device.

00:22:38.160 --> 00:22:41.790
Earlier at I/O, we mentioned
that the Assistant is

00:22:41.790 --> 00:22:45.120
on over 500 million devices--

00:22:45.120 --> 00:22:49.210
smart speakers, phones, watches,
headphones, Chromebooks, cars,

00:22:49.210 --> 00:22:50.550
TVs.

00:22:50.550 --> 00:22:53.520
And with the Assistant
SDK, device makers

00:22:53.520 --> 00:22:56.100
are embedding the system in
more devices all the time.

00:22:59.360 --> 00:23:01.670
When designing for
multiple devices,

00:23:01.670 --> 00:23:04.740
there's a spectrum of
capabilities to consider.

00:23:04.740 --> 00:23:07.840
Sometimes its voice
only, like a Google Home.

00:23:07.840 --> 00:23:09.410
And with new smart
screens, there's

00:23:09.410 --> 00:23:11.840
a mix of visual and touch.

00:23:11.840 --> 00:23:15.050
Sometimes the same device
falls on different parts

00:23:15.050 --> 00:23:17.930
of the spectrum, depending
upon the user's context,

00:23:17.930 --> 00:23:21.834
like they're driving
or the volume is muted.

00:23:21.834 --> 00:23:24.500
So these are the things you need
to take into consideration when

00:23:24.500 --> 00:23:27.100
designing for these.

00:23:27.100 --> 00:23:30.340
Let's take an example
of a surf report.

00:23:30.340 --> 00:23:32.800
On a smart speaker
like a Google Home,

00:23:32.800 --> 00:23:35.720
the report needs to be
presented with just speech.

00:23:35.720 --> 00:23:38.230
So in this example,
the whole interaction

00:23:38.230 --> 00:23:41.710
is verbal and through audio.

00:23:41.710 --> 00:23:45.190
Now, that same one on the
right is with a screen.

00:23:45.190 --> 00:23:49.480
Here, the audio or the verbal
presentation is abridged,

00:23:49.480 --> 00:23:51.310
but then now there's
a visual presentation

00:23:51.310 --> 00:23:52.850
that goes along with it.

00:23:52.850 --> 00:23:56.170
And we encourage you to use
these rich visual presentations

00:23:56.170 --> 00:23:58.270
on devices with screens.

00:23:58.270 --> 00:24:00.140
And even on the bottom,
on the bottom right,

00:24:00.140 --> 00:24:03.490
you can see that the choices are
presented as suggestion chips.

00:24:03.490 --> 00:24:05.230
So the user can
tap on them instead

00:24:05.230 --> 00:24:07.240
of having to speak on a
device with the screen.

00:24:11.540 --> 00:24:13.750
And implementing such
logic is straightforward

00:24:13.750 --> 00:24:18.260
using surface capabilities APIs
and some conditional logic.

00:24:18.260 --> 00:24:21.110
Now, there is so much
more about this topic.

00:24:21.110 --> 00:24:23.870
Fortunately, there is a
whole talk about it Wednesday

00:24:23.870 --> 00:24:27.560
at 11:30 called Design Actions
for the Google Assistant,

00:24:27.560 --> 00:24:29.930
Beyond Smart Speakers to
Phones and Smart Displays.

00:24:35.570 --> 00:24:38.090
A great way to see if
your actions are working

00:24:38.090 --> 00:24:41.230
are putting them in
the hands of users.

00:24:41.230 --> 00:24:44.540
But you might want to try things
out with a smaller audience

00:24:44.540 --> 00:24:47.120
before you launch to
a bigger audience.

00:24:47.120 --> 00:24:49.460
Now, we just released
a new tool that

00:24:49.460 --> 00:24:51.770
lets you test with
smaller audiences,

00:24:51.770 --> 00:24:55.490
and there's two options with it.

00:24:55.490 --> 00:24:57.220
You can do an alpha release.

00:24:57.220 --> 00:24:59.600
Your action goes through
a limited review.

00:24:59.600 --> 00:25:03.020
And this is great to get
early feedback on your action.

00:25:03.020 --> 00:25:05.280
Give it out to a
small test group.

00:25:05.280 --> 00:25:08.690
And one of the other
advantages of alpha releases

00:25:08.690 --> 00:25:13.520
is that the review process is
much shorter, within hours.

00:25:13.520 --> 00:25:16.820
So that way you can just make
a fix, test it with some users,

00:25:16.820 --> 00:25:21.080
and iterate very, very quickly
and get that feedback you need.

00:25:21.080 --> 00:25:24.380
So that when you're releasing
to a larger audience,

00:25:24.380 --> 00:25:28.960
you've gotten through all the
bugs and all the design issues.

00:25:28.960 --> 00:25:31.620
The second option is
doing a beta release.

00:25:31.620 --> 00:25:34.140
This is intended when you're
near feature complete,

00:25:34.140 --> 00:25:37.410
and you have a stable version
or a near stable version.

00:25:37.410 --> 00:25:40.170
Test this with a wider audience.

00:25:40.170 --> 00:25:44.280
Now, beta goes through the full
typical approval for actions,

00:25:44.280 --> 00:25:47.010
but there's an additional
advantage with this.

00:25:47.010 --> 00:25:51.120
You can control when you take
an action from beta to public.

00:25:51.120 --> 00:25:53.790
So that way, if you're
trying to time or release

00:25:53.790 --> 00:25:56.220
based on your marketing
considerations,

00:25:56.220 --> 00:25:57.270
you can keep it in beta.

00:25:57.270 --> 00:26:00.360
And then when you are ready for
it to go live, flip the switch

00:26:00.360 --> 00:26:03.090
and make it go
live to the public.

00:26:07.850 --> 00:26:09.700
Now, after you've
built your action

00:26:09.700 --> 00:26:13.380
and test it and launch it, it's
great to see what happened.

00:26:13.380 --> 00:26:15.334
How many users are coming back?

00:26:15.334 --> 00:26:16.500
Or how many users are there?

00:26:16.500 --> 00:26:18.720
How many are coming back?

00:26:18.720 --> 00:26:23.260
What problems, if any,
are they encountering?

00:26:23.260 --> 00:26:27.030
For traditional metrics, like
traffic, errors and retention,

00:26:27.030 --> 00:26:30.300
there are existing analytics
you can use to see these.

00:26:30.300 --> 00:26:32.340
You can find the two on
the left on the Actions

00:26:32.340 --> 00:26:34.200
on Google Console.

00:26:34.200 --> 00:26:36.600
Retention, like a
cohort analysis,

00:26:36.600 --> 00:26:39.510
is available through another
tool called Chatbase.

00:26:39.510 --> 00:26:42.810
Chatbase is a tool that you
can integrate with your action

00:26:42.810 --> 00:26:45.732
where you can get deeper
conversational analytics.

00:26:45.732 --> 00:26:47.190
And speaking about
some things that

00:26:47.190 --> 00:26:50.070
are conversational
and analytic, let's

00:26:50.070 --> 00:26:52.650
take a look at something that's
particular to conversational

00:26:52.650 --> 00:26:53.510
analytics.

00:26:53.510 --> 00:26:55.980
And this is called
a session flow.

00:26:55.980 --> 00:27:00.150
Here, you can see the pathways
a user takes most often.

00:27:00.150 --> 00:27:03.690
The green paths are the ones
that your action handled.

00:27:03.690 --> 00:27:06.370
The red paths are not handled.

00:27:06.370 --> 00:27:08.700
So in this example,
book a hotel,

00:27:08.700 --> 00:27:11.190
when a user says book a
hotel, that was handled.

00:27:11.190 --> 00:27:15.340
But when a user says
feedback, it wasn't handled.

00:27:15.340 --> 00:27:17.520
Now, when we talked
about no match errors

00:27:17.520 --> 00:27:20.430
before in the
robust grammars tip,

00:27:20.430 --> 00:27:24.600
here is where you can see how
often these no matches happen

00:27:24.600 --> 00:27:28.260
and where you can figure out how
to prioritize addressing these.

00:27:28.260 --> 00:27:31.240
Both Dialogflow and Chatbase
include a session flow view.

00:27:34.070 --> 00:27:36.150
And if you need
to drill down, you

00:27:36.150 --> 00:27:38.500
can see transcripts,
including the individual steps

00:27:38.500 --> 00:27:39.570
the user went.

00:27:39.570 --> 00:27:42.259
So you can see what led
up to a potential problem.

00:27:42.259 --> 00:27:43.550
So you can try to address that.

00:27:46.310 --> 00:27:50.660
To recap, enhance your actions
to take them to the next level

00:27:50.660 --> 00:27:54.890
and increase engagement,
personalize it to the user,

00:27:54.890 --> 00:27:58.280
add sounds, account
for actions running

00:27:58.280 --> 00:28:00.140
on different types of devices--

00:28:00.140 --> 00:28:03.080
for example, some with
screen, some not--

00:28:03.080 --> 00:28:04.910
test it with smaller audiences.

00:28:04.910 --> 00:28:07.820
And then when you launch,
use the analytics tools here

00:28:07.820 --> 00:28:09.170
to see what the users are doing.

00:28:13.409 --> 00:28:16.340
TORI BURMEISTER: So now
you built your awesome app.

00:28:16.340 --> 00:28:19.300
You want to engage your
users and reach many more.

00:28:22.970 --> 00:28:25.310
Tip 10, re-engage your users.

00:28:28.460 --> 00:28:30.890
During normal interactions
with your action,

00:28:30.890 --> 00:28:34.220
you can ask users to opt
in to receive updates

00:28:34.220 --> 00:28:36.750
using two subscription models.

00:28:36.750 --> 00:28:39.120
The first is daily
updates where Google

00:28:39.120 --> 00:28:43.080
pulls an update at a time
specified by the user.

00:28:43.080 --> 00:28:46.940
The second is push notifications
where the action can

00:28:46.940 --> 00:28:49.460
push updates when appropriate.

00:28:49.460 --> 00:28:51.620
These notifications
work on the phone

00:28:51.620 --> 00:28:55.400
even if you don't have
an Android app installed.

00:28:55.400 --> 00:28:57.950
And now, with cross
surface notifications

00:28:57.950 --> 00:28:59.750
coming to the Google
Assistant, you'll

00:28:59.750 --> 00:29:02.870
be able to reach your users
on speakers, smart displays,

00:29:02.870 --> 00:29:04.370
and other Google devices.

00:29:08.070 --> 00:29:10.470
Here's an example
of tube status.

00:29:10.470 --> 00:29:14.170
This can keep you up to date
on your commute conditions.

00:29:14.170 --> 00:29:19.387
Here is an example of the user
configuring the daily update.

00:29:19.387 --> 00:29:20.970
Here's what it looks
like when they're

00:29:20.970 --> 00:29:26.190
getting the update, as
well as a notification when

00:29:26.190 --> 00:29:28.230
there are severe delays.

00:29:28.230 --> 00:29:29.340
Great way to re-engage.

00:29:34.290 --> 00:29:36.990
If you want the user
to get daily updates,

00:29:36.990 --> 00:29:40.920
you can actually set this up
using the Actions Console.

00:29:40.920 --> 00:29:44.940
The second way is in your
web hook in your code.

00:29:44.940 --> 00:29:49.770
Here, you create a new
register update object.

00:29:49.770 --> 00:29:52.020
You can put in arguments--

00:29:52.020 --> 00:29:56.310
here, horoscope sign,
and then the frequency.

00:29:56.310 --> 00:30:00.060
Other examples of
daily updates are a tip

00:30:00.060 --> 00:30:02.130
of the day or a surf report.

00:30:05.850 --> 00:30:08.250
Now, notifications and
updates can be a great way

00:30:08.250 --> 00:30:12.030
to re-engage with your
users, but they can also

00:30:12.030 --> 00:30:13.740
be really annoying.

00:30:13.740 --> 00:30:16.710
You have to be careful
to make it relevant.

00:30:16.710 --> 00:30:21.660
So use personalization-- results
for the user's favorite club

00:30:21.660 --> 00:30:23.970
instead of the whole league.

00:30:23.970 --> 00:30:26.310
Be descriptive--
users will receive

00:30:26.310 --> 00:30:29.250
the title and the
notification, so describe

00:30:29.250 --> 00:30:31.920
the content they are
receiving and don't just

00:30:31.920 --> 00:30:34.140
list the name of the action.

00:30:34.140 --> 00:30:37.680
And third, don't
spam your users--

00:30:37.680 --> 00:30:41.270
make sure the information
is relevant to them

00:30:41.270 --> 00:30:42.080
or don't do it.

00:30:45.650 --> 00:30:50.930
Tip 11, make your
action easy to discover.

00:30:50.930 --> 00:30:53.960
We're working hard to make
sure all great actions are

00:30:53.960 --> 00:30:55.400
discoverable.

00:30:55.400 --> 00:30:58.520
And there are three main
ways to get discovered--

00:30:58.520 --> 00:31:02.330
the first is the Assistant
Explore Directory.

00:31:02.330 --> 00:31:06.200
The second is when the user
is talking to the Assistant,

00:31:06.200 --> 00:31:08.960
make sure you come
up as an option.

00:31:08.960 --> 00:31:11.600
And the third is
action links, which

00:31:11.600 --> 00:31:13.700
are hyperlinks to
your action which

00:31:13.700 --> 00:31:14.960
you can add to any surface.

00:31:20.490 --> 00:31:23.820
The best way to ensure
you're discovered?

00:31:23.820 --> 00:31:26.130
Make it good.

00:31:26.130 --> 00:31:29.700
We check each action, and the
higher the quality, the return

00:31:29.700 --> 00:31:32.700
rate, health, and
ratings, the more likely

00:31:32.700 --> 00:31:35.760
we'll highlight your action.

00:31:35.760 --> 00:31:38.430
Follow the design principles
in the Developer docs

00:31:38.430 --> 00:31:40.140
to help guide you.

00:31:40.140 --> 00:31:42.270
We have some great
stuff out there.

00:31:42.270 --> 00:31:45.330
There are also several
talks at I/O that will help.

00:31:49.390 --> 00:31:51.640
Here's the Assistant
Explore Directory.

00:31:51.640 --> 00:31:56.410
It's available on the web at
assistant.Google.com/explore

00:31:56.410 --> 00:32:00.700
and in an app in
both Android and iOS.

00:32:00.700 --> 00:32:03.280
The directory is very
important because we

00:32:03.280 --> 00:32:06.424
see that 30% of our
third party actions

00:32:06.424 --> 00:32:07.840
are getting
discovered through it.

00:32:10.430 --> 00:32:12.830
So when a user is
browsing, you want

00:32:12.830 --> 00:32:16.020
to make sure you get discovered.

00:32:16.020 --> 00:32:20.930
The first browsing option
are contextual suggestions.

00:32:20.930 --> 00:32:24.340
These relevant suggestions are
based on the user's contexts,

00:32:24.340 --> 00:32:26.190
such as the time
of day or location.

00:32:29.260 --> 00:32:32.080
The second is
dynamic categories.

00:32:32.080 --> 00:32:35.350
These are things like
what's new, what's trending,

00:32:35.350 --> 00:32:36.670
what's popular.

00:32:36.670 --> 00:32:38.900
And now we have editorial picks.

00:32:38.900 --> 00:32:41.680
This is a new feature
highlighting high quality

00:32:41.680 --> 00:32:43.660
actions through
visual campaigns.

00:32:47.940 --> 00:32:49.710
You now know that
high quality is

00:32:49.710 --> 00:32:53.130
the key to being featured
in the Assistant Directory.

00:32:53.130 --> 00:32:56.520
To trigger more naturally
in conversation,

00:32:56.520 --> 00:32:58.410
use built-in intents.

00:32:58.410 --> 00:33:00.630
This is currently in preview.

00:33:00.630 --> 00:33:04.560
It allows actions to trigger
for relevant queries that

00:33:04.560 --> 00:33:06.750
are more general.

00:33:06.750 --> 00:33:11.040
These built-in intents provided
common taxonomy for actions

00:33:11.040 --> 00:33:14.130
across all Google surfaces.

00:33:14.130 --> 00:33:17.010
Google Assistant
parses the user query

00:33:17.010 --> 00:33:21.690
and passes it as structured data
so developers don't have to.

00:33:21.690 --> 00:33:26.250
Using these general intents is
much more natural for users.

00:33:26.250 --> 00:33:30.270
In this way, users don't
have to use your action name.

00:33:30.270 --> 00:33:33.720
A couple examples of built-in
intents are tell a joke

00:33:33.720 --> 00:33:35.580
or start a calming activity.

00:33:39.580 --> 00:33:42.850
In Dialogflow, you can
select the built-in intent

00:33:42.850 --> 00:33:46.360
you'd like to be associated with
and then add in parameters that

00:33:46.360 --> 00:33:48.850
can be passed into your action.

00:33:48.850 --> 00:33:51.610
Today, we're making the
first set of these intents

00:33:51.610 --> 00:33:54.670
available so you can give
the Assistant a deeper

00:33:54.670 --> 00:33:57.310
understanding of what
your action can do.

00:33:57.310 --> 00:33:59.870
And we'll be rolling
out hundreds more

00:33:59.870 --> 00:34:00.745
in the coming months.

00:34:04.430 --> 00:34:08.530
So the third way to get
discovered is action links.

00:34:08.530 --> 00:34:12.020
They're hyperlinks that point
directly into your action.

00:34:12.020 --> 00:34:14.060
They make your
actions discoverable

00:34:14.060 --> 00:34:16.670
from any platform
or surface, and they

00:34:16.670 --> 00:34:20.000
allow users to engage
directly with your action

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:22.909
irrespective of how
they found your link.

00:34:22.909 --> 00:34:24.880
The links can be
added anywhere--

00:34:24.880 --> 00:34:27.889
websites, social
campaigns, and more.

00:34:31.659 --> 00:34:35.020
It's really simple to
set up action links.

00:34:35.020 --> 00:34:39.130
You need to go into the Actions
console, publish a URL link,

00:34:39.130 --> 00:34:41.810
and give it a title,
and then share away.

00:34:45.469 --> 00:34:49.690
A final tip, be helpful
everywhere your users are.

00:34:52.989 --> 00:34:57.970
We're launched in more than
25 locales in 16 languages.

00:34:57.970 --> 00:35:01.300
We recommend engaging
with this global audience

00:35:01.300 --> 00:35:02.140
as soon as possible.

00:35:05.370 --> 00:35:07.620
Flicks Bus is a bus
company, and it's

00:35:07.620 --> 00:35:10.770
available in multiple
countries and languages.

00:35:10.770 --> 00:35:13.380
Here, you can see
identical action screens

00:35:13.380 --> 00:35:14.820
in multiple languages--

00:35:14.820 --> 00:35:17.190
English, French, and German.

00:35:22.200 --> 00:35:23.610
And here, we're
going to show you

00:35:23.610 --> 00:35:27.120
how to efficiently localize
your action using a third party

00:35:27.120 --> 00:35:29.220
localization library.

00:35:29.220 --> 00:35:33.510
The first thing to do is
create a locales directory

00:35:33.510 --> 00:35:35.520
and a resource file
or a translation

00:35:35.520 --> 00:35:37.290
file for each locale.

00:35:37.290 --> 00:35:38.955
In this example, it's en-us.

00:35:38.955 --> 00:35:41.380
JSON.

00:35:41.380 --> 00:35:45.090
That stands for
English, United States.

00:35:45.090 --> 00:35:47.790
Then, within the file,
you create a constant

00:35:47.790 --> 00:35:53.790
for each string in your
action along with the string.

00:35:53.790 --> 00:35:57.090
Then, for each
additional language,

00:35:57.090 --> 00:36:00.690
you create a new JSON file
and use the same constants

00:36:00.690 --> 00:36:03.090
but have translated strings.

00:36:03.090 --> 00:36:04.820
There are many
translation services

00:36:04.820 --> 00:36:05.820
that can help with this.

00:36:09.990 --> 00:36:15.440
And then in your web hook, you
use the i18 and node library

00:36:15.440 --> 00:36:17.840
to do the hard work.

00:36:17.840 --> 00:36:22.280
Here, you're going to
configure the i18n object.

00:36:22.280 --> 00:36:24.890
You're going to set the
locales you want to support,

00:36:24.890 --> 00:36:27.520
where the translation
files are located,

00:36:27.520 --> 00:36:28.520
and your default locale.

00:36:31.580 --> 00:36:34.160
Then, when the
conversation starts,

00:36:34.160 --> 00:36:37.220
you're going to set
that specific user's

00:36:37.220 --> 00:36:39.435
locale in the i18n object.

00:36:42.850 --> 00:36:45.180
And finally, throughout
the conversation,

00:36:45.180 --> 00:36:49.350
you use these constants instead
of conditional statements.

00:36:49.350 --> 00:36:51.630
This greatly simplifies
the complexity

00:36:51.630 --> 00:36:53.160
of supporting
multiple languages.

